SIMPLE: fluff
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Fluff
<hw>Fluff</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. 2d <er>Flue</er>.
⟦root⟧84.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Nap or down; flue[2]; soft, downy
feathers.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <specif>Hence:</specif> <def>Anything light and downy,
whose volume consists mostly of air, such as cotton or down.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Something light and inconsequential; something not
to be taken seriously; -- used commonly of literary or dramatic
productions, and sometimes of people.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>A mistake, especially in the recitation of lines in
a drama.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Fluff</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Fluff
<hw>Fluff</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t. & i.</pos> <def>To make or
become fluffy; to move lightly like fluff.</def>
<rj><au>Holmes.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Fluff</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Fluff
<hw>Fluff</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To make a mistake in
the performance of; -- used mostly of lines in a drama; <as>as, he
<ex>fluffed</ex> the last line of the act</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Fluffy</ent>⟦br⟧
